SIMPLE: sluice
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sluice
<hw>Sluice</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>escluse</ets>, F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧cluse</ets>, LL. <ets>exclusa</ets>,
<ets>sclusa</ets>, from L. <ets>excludere</ets>, <ets>exclusum</ets>, to
shut out: cf. D. <ets>sluis</ets> sluice, from the Old French. See
<er>Exclude</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An artifical passage for
water, fitted with a valve or gate, as in a mill stream, for stopping or
regulating the flow; also, a water gate or flood gate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, an opening or channel through which anything
flows; a source of supply.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each <qex>sluice</qex> of affluent fortune opened soon.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This home familiarity . . . opens the <qex>sluices</qex> of
sensibility.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The stream flowing through a flood gate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A long box or trough through
which water flows, -- used for washing auriferous earth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sluice gate</b></col>, <cd>the sliding gate of a
sluice.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sluice</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sluice
<hw>Sluice</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sluiced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sluicing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To emit
by, or as by, flood gates.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To wet copiously, as by opening a sluice; <as>as, to
<ex>sluice</ex> meadows</as>.</def> <rj><au>Howitt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He dried his neck and face, which he had been <qex>sluicing</qex>
with cold water.</q> <rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wash with, or in, a stream of water running
through a sluice; <as>as, to <ex>sluice</ex> eart or gold dust in
mining</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sluiceway</ent>⟦br⟧
